The words of Victorinus are, “Antiqui pro reri, cedron scribebant, sed quum nostra aetas partem literarum in eo reservarit, partem, brevitatis causa, ex eo detraxerit, nonnullam immutarit, et nos per red quam per set scribamus;'' where observe that he says umbrosanum scri- demas: a few lines before he had observed, “ sed nos nunc et ahenam et aprtd per D potius quam per T scribamus, omentum et apur.”

Again, the earne Victorinus (p. 2462) derives haud from oi, and lays it down as a rule that it ought to be written houd when the word following begins with a vowel, as houd aperilem, but haut when the word following begins with a consonant, as lou! pluuium but this

must be regarded as an opinion of what ought to be done, not as the record of an established usage. The forms haud and haut were probably both in common use when Victorinus composed his treatise; and he sought to establish a distinction as to their use. Ritschl (Proleg. XCIX, Q), who has a pet theory of his own with regard to the form lou, which mayor may not have been occasionally enr- ployed* reconstructs the above passage, and endeavours to convince us that the precept which Victorinus intended to incurate was that we ought to write haud before a vowel and hau before a consonent.

But without attempting to penetrate farther into the thomy thicket of these grammatical speculatione, it may be stated as a fact that the forms At, Aput, Set, Alnus, Haut, for Ad, Apud, Sed, Aliud, Haud, and also It, Qait, Quot, for Id, Qm'd, Quod, occur not unfrequently in inscriptions and the oldest MSS, and hence Bentley has admitted Aput, Set, Haut, into the text of his Terence, while Ritschl adopts these and also aliid and illut.
